e": 1525337070000}, "author": "Aslioch", "author_id": "2118185", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "The weathering reaction of olivine (the main mineral in the rock dunite) with CO2 and water is as follows:Equ.1 4CO2 + 2H2O + Mg2SiO4(s) => SiO2(s) + 2Mg2+(aq) + 4HCO3-(aq)As you can see, no hydrogen ions (ie acid) are produced in that process. On the contrary, CO2 is being removed from the atmosphere, thus reducing the partial pressure of atmospheric CO2 below what it would otherwise be and therefore reducing the amount of CO2 dissolving in the oceans via the (simplified) reaction:Equ.2 CO2 + H2O <=> H+(aq) + HCO3-(aq).If those 4 bicarbonate ions from the weathering of the olivine eventually react to produce limestone in the sea, then the overall reaction is:Equ.3 2Ca2+(aq) + 4HCO3-(aq) => 2CaCO3(s) + 2H2O + 2CO2Combining the equations 1 & 3 shows that overall 2 moles (4 minus 2) of CO2 have been sequestrated as CaCO3 for every mole of Mg2SiO4 weathered. (Initially 4 moles of CO2 are removed from the atmosphere during the weathering process and then 2 moles of CO2 are released into sea water during limestone formation).", "recommendation_count": "1", "in_reply_to": "115338413", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "115376121", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1525294344000}, "author": "Yetypu", "author_id": "4669086", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "BQSTART\nYes, coring basalt is a task\nBQEND\nWeatherford decided on a training school in Aberdeen, with some real wells for simulation. The first 4,000 ft below surface in Aberdeen is granite.\nHalliburton put their training well {puit} in Montrose - much easier.", "recommendation_count": "0", "in_reply_to": "115373365", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "115375515", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1525292484000}, "author": "glacier", "author_id": "4706143", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "Sure. \nThis is how nature does it and changed our climate and pCO2 from \"dinosaur conditions\" to the \"Plio-Pleistocene conditions\" over tens of millions of years. \nIt is also literally a \"stone-age\" solution to a \"stone-age\" problem. Artificially speeding up rock-erosion to solve artificial change to the geological carbon-cycle. \nThe fossil industry lives in this reality of physics: The joy of fossil fuel is based on the same thermodynamics as AGW. Fossil fuel gives off energy when one burn it. But to collect and bind the waste-product (although it can be done) simply does not add up when scaled to the energy produced in the first step (and the price it is sold for). \nThis means that CO2 levels will eventually go back to natural - because of rocks. But it takes the age of human civilisations times thousands to do it properly - after being left alone. \nThere is only one solution to this problem - to scale back our mucking about with the geological carbon cycle - to zero. \nEven if we price energy on the level that carbon can be profitable with CCS (meaning that the profit from making energy from wind and solar will be crazy high and cause fossil to collapse instantly) - the efficiency of CCS is still too low. \nCCS research is still needed, though - for non-fossil applications such as cement-production etc. \nFinally - this is science. It looks into the effect industrial scale crushing of rocks (similar in size to global industrial scale fossil geology) - and ends up with a 10% \"effect\". It is bleedingly obvious that it will be the fossil companies that will pay for the hundreds of thousands of jobs and machinery for this global scale dunite and basalt mining and crushing and fertilisation project. It will be billed to customers on the electricity and fuel-price at the petrol-station. \nIt is how science does a bit of sarcasm. Sure the laws of the universe can make your emission problem a bit smaller. \nScience did the same sarcasm with the CCS dream. Sure science can help you design a CCS plant. No problem. But you must pay for it's construction - and you must offset 30% of the coal you buy - and burn it non-profit to give the energy for the CCS-system (if you do not want to invest in a lot of wind-mills or solar farms to provide that energy).Then you must send these numbers over to your economics section and ponder what you can sell \"clean fossils\" for \nNo fossil companies talk about CCS any longer. Funny that.", "recommendation_count": "2", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "rocks", "effect": "that co2 levels will eventually go back to natural"}, {"cause": "the profit from making energy from wind and solar", "effect": "fossil"}]}, {"id": "115373365", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1525288748000}, "author": "rockyrex", "author_id": "2923581", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "Yes, coring basalt is a task .....\nOurs was from limestones and shales from the Wenlock sequences in an inlier in the South Staffordshire Coalfield.", "recommendation_count": "3", "in_reply_to": "115373210", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "115373210", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1525288485000}, "author": "Yetypu", "author_id": "4669086", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "BQSTART\nIt made quite a feature\nBQEND\nI imagine it would. Nice one.\nMust get my eyes checked - didn't recognise it for what it was: une produit de carotage.\nThat would use up a little rig time - coring basalt.\nApologies Grauniad subeditor - good title. The carbonate is still within a matrix of basalt tho'.", "recommendation_count": "1", "in_reply_to": "115367118", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "115367714", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1525279768000}, "author": "mustardpat", "author_id": "10146019", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "\"Pricewise, the technique would cost about 10 times as much as afforestation and about two to four times as much as carbon capture and storage.\"If that sentence had been put at the start of the article........", "recommendation_count": "1", "causal_relation