 planet in 50 years- however there is a variable - us. If we made a global effort to massively reduce CO2 then that would change the outcome.\nPredictions can be made- I can book a rail ticket for 6 months time, I know when I have to submit my tax returns next year- and a range of outcomes for global temperature can be made now- but it is a big range from 1.5C [unlikely] to 3C [likely] to 8c [unlikely].\nHow do you suggest we proceed?", "recommendation_count": "5", "in_reply_to": "115621380", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "human activity", "effect": "recent warming"}, {"cause": "the stakes are so high", "effect": "the science is far more vigorous"}]}, {"id": "115621845", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1525890323000}, "author": "ComfortablyPlumb", "author_id": "14842422", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "BQSTART\nYou have taken 'dangerous' and given your own interpretation on the subject- i.e. the death count.\nBQENDDo you have a reason to believe the casualty figures will follow a different trend?\nIf so (as seems) then explain- \nBQSTART\nI don't know the exact meaning of the broad use of the word- nuclear material is a hazard to human health\nBQENDSo is fly ash and slag.\nWorking 200m in the air is Hazardous - even more so if you're at sea.\nCleaning bird poop and leaves from rooftop solar panels is hazardous - as is installing them.\nYou may not think it's important, but tell that to the families.\nBQSTART\nChernobyl has had indirect health effects on people-\nBQENDHere we go....\n22,ooo people a year die in Europe because of our coal burning - that's nearly five times the maximum total; figure that the WHO and UNSCEAR model for the entirety of Chernobyl, an accident in an uncontained reactor design that does not exist anymore in a state that ceased to exist - basic food measures would have prevented nearly all of it.\nhttp://www.unscear.org/http://www.world-nuclear.org/information-library/safety-and-security/safety-of-plants/chernobyl-accident.