rumental data in recent decades (since about 1980) - the very period when warming is argued to be at its strongest. It's called the Divergence Problem. It is well known amongst climate scientists. However, they dismiss it as unimportant without providing any scientific evidence of why its not important. They don't know beyond speculating: 'we think its to do with modern air pollution'. It's so simple to understand, it even has a Wikipedia entry. \"It is the disagreement between the temperatures measured by the thermometers (instrumental temperatures) and the temperatures reconstructed from the latewood densities or, in some cases, widths of tree rings in the far northern forests....The deviation of some tree ring proxy measurements from the instrumental record since the 1950s raises the question of the reliability of tree ring proxies in the period before the instrumental temperature record.\"\"Some\" records? Michael Mann et al stated in a comprehensive proxy study: \nBQSTART\nthe observed warming rises above the error bounds of the estimates during the 1980s decade, consistent with the known \u2018\u2018divergence problem\u2019\u2019, wherein the temperature sensitivity of some temperature-sensitive tree-ring data appears to have declined in the most recent decades. Interestingly, although the elimination of all tree-ring data from the proxy dataset yields a substantially smaller divergence bias, it does not eliminate the problem altogether\nBQEND\nAnd why is it so important? As\nD'Arrigo et al state:\n\nBQSTART\nreconstructions based on northern tree-ring data impacted by divergence cannot be used to directly compare past natural warm periods (notably, the MWP) with recent 20th century warming, making it more difficult to state unequivocally that the recent warming is unprecedented.\nBQEND\nSo, Graham Redferan, please investigate this, if only to reassure yourself the Divergence problem does not undermine the case for CAGW.\nUnderstanding this will give you a muc