n species numbers and total biomass.\n3. Shift to public transport - car usage (as well as needing more roads) increases nitrogen content near roads which causes homogenisation of plants (cow parlsely, nettles and brambles do well - other things such as poppies and other flowers that have evolved to do well in low nitrogen soils do worse) and this has a knock on effect on the diversity of species that can be supported.\n4. More joined up planning - the ever increasing trend for these estates of 3/4/5 bedroom houses outside towns that have no amenities and no bus access is driving the eating up of habitat.\n5. Stop paving over gardens (which I appreciate you might not have done!) but it's a real scourge!\n6. Support (and government needs to fund) programmes to reduce invasive species, for insects things like rhododendron might seem good but they are hugely invasive and drive out pretty much all other plants (which leads to a reduction in insect biodveirsty)\n7. Support local wildlife trusts - this one is important as wildlife trusts (when they can) buy new land to be protected (in Norfolk for example they bought Hickling broad about a year ago - it's the largest and most important broad for wildlife)", "recommendation_count": "0", "in_reply_to": "116068601", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "which", "effect": "homogenisation of plants"}, {"cause": "which", "effect": "a reduction in insect biodveirsty"}]}, {"id": "116050828", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1526898305000}, "author": "Harvestingkarma", "author_id": "16314139", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "Governments may be career building and business building! The vote is a kind of soother of the people. I think the governments kind of have ways of making sure the party that gets in is the one that the top johnnies think is right for us. People do not think for themselves, they go along with the flow and media manipulation is subtle..", "recommendation_count": "0", "in_reply_to": "116044565", "causa