ying (but rarely acknowledged) visions for social development:\n1. The classic economic vision: Favoured across a wide spectrum from Marxist-Leninist to Libertarian Capitalist. A rapid economic growth vision predicated on treating the environment as a \u2018free good\u2019 to be exploited at will.\n2. The environment primacy vision: Likewise having proponents across the Left-Right political spectrum. A social, cultural & environment continuity & stability vision that focuses on the negative impacts of unrestrained growth.\nViewed as extremes in isolation, Vision 1 encourages bitter end commitment to hydrocarbon fuel industry development while Vision 2 encourages precipitous shutdown of that industry regardless of negative economic, & social impacts.\nThe Federal Conservative party has embraced the classic economic vision with only scant acknowledgment of the environmental implications while the Federal NDP has largely embraced the environment primacy vision with only bare outlines of a strategy to address the economic implications of a rapid & vigorous transition away from carbon fuels. Both these stances enjoy support in various regions of Canada & equally strong opposition in other regions.\nThe Liberals, to their credit, have tried to find a viable symbiosis transcending these 2 visions. However, they have seriously underestimated the need for a frank debate to rally support for such a symbiosis. They are further hindered by the failure of the Ontario Liberal Government to devise & bring into effect in practice such a symbiosis Provincially.\nIn short, the Liberals are aimed in the right direction but have been less than stellar in execution to date.", "recommendation_count": "2", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "116417744", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1527694552000}, "author": "SH1988", "author_id": "100134899", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "I think what has been lost here is the fact that this is a global issue. When this oil gets burnt