 whilst waiting hungrily for the ice to form, so that's not going to happen). And once bears can't reproduce, the local population must move or die out. And moving isn't always viable - you need to be able to find a region with both food and sufficient ice days\nSome areas that have populations may be lucky in the sense that local climate dynamics will allow sea ice days to remain at sufficient levels to support a population, but given the factors forcing the climate to change, you wouldn't want to bet anything you care about on it.", "recommendation_count": "1", "in_reply_to": "116239923", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "116276427", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1527383675000}, "author": "RJander", "author_id": "15758543", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "So the existence of a species that the Inuit have co-existed with and admired for millennia is some kind of threat to the survival of the human race. Wow.", "recommendation_count": "3", "in_reply_to": "116241441", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "116276336", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1527383216000}, "author": "Lotharsson", "author_id": "14463693", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "BQSTART\n...as i wasn't referring to the Inuit...\nBQEND\nSo when you said:\nBQSTART\n...they just use culture & tradition as an excuse to carry on the decimation...\nBQEND\n...in response to a comment talking about the Inuit hunting polar bears in Labrador, you were actually talking about \"the Right wing hunting fraternity\"?\nI must admit I do find you hard to follow at times.", "recommendation_count": "0", "in_reply_to": "116241615", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "116276239", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1527382792000}, "author": "Lotharsson", "author_id": "14463693", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "BQSTART\nThe following link supports the claim that the Inuit are not making a traditional living relying on Polar bear meat as a reliable consistent staple to their diet,... \nOnce again debunking the myth of a culture coexisting with nature as part of an ecologically functioning comunity...\nBQEND\nFirstly, it's a red herring to suggest that the argument is that Inuit should only be allowed to hunt because they've traditionally hunted for meat. For one thing, traditionally they've used pretty much every part of the animal, and they've also hunted in defence.\nSecondly, the argument that Inuit should be allowed to continue hunting references their culture long before present day, not just \"now\", and as the 2nd paragraph of your linked article points out:\nBQSTART\nInuit have hunted polar bears as an element of their overall set of ecological relations for millennia with this hunting (see Nelson 1970; Robbe 1975; Wenzel 1981) being conducted for spiritual-cultural reasons and to contribute to the traditional food economy.\nBQEND\nIn other words, it pretty much says that polar bear is part of their diet and has been for a long long time, and (if you look into it) eating polar bear is not just about calories but has a community/cultural/spiritual dimension.\nAnd whilst the document does go on to point out that the subsistence role of polar bears changed \"in the last 50 years or so\" to include some sports hunting, it rebuts your apparent view and the objection based on it (as I read it in comments you made elsewhere) that polar bear hunting was not a significant part of a cultural - or culinary - tradition at any time in Inuit history, so we can dispense with that line of argument.\nThe document does discuss present day (up to about the year 2000) sport hunting and social and economic factors that have motivated more of it since about 1970, which seems more relevant to your position. You can argue that sports hunting should not be allowed, and I had a lot more sympathy with that position before I talked to the polar bear tour guides - who you'd think of all people would object, but they accept it, given the cultural significance of bear hunting and the resulting use of the animal, and the realities of living in the far north. \nHowever, more importantly, you also appear to conclude that this document supports your key claim that the Inuit don't coexist with nature as part of an ecologically functioning community, but I'm not sure that follows either, at least not as most people would interpret the term \"ecologically functioning community\" which would probably indicate living in such a fashion as to maintain the local ecosystem in a reasonably ecologically-sustainable fashion (and which the government-managed harvest scheme appears to be attempting to do).\nSo when you say \"ecologically functioning community\" here, do you intend to imply \"not aided by a single drop of oil\", which you clarified elsewhere was intended to be understood when you use the term \"sustainable\"? Or, since you say:\nBQSTART\nIt's all about the MONEY.\nBQEND\n...do you mean something like \"without using money as a medium of exchange for any resource obtained from the ecosystem, or for any tools used for obtaining said resources\"?\nIf so, it seems a bit rich if not outright hypocritical to be complaining that the Inuit don't get to adopt money in their culture, or should drop or decline to evolve millennia-old elements of their culture because they can make money from it, when you and I and all of our fellow readers are living in Western capitalist (it's all about the MONEY!) societies that have a much bigger negative impact on the earth's ecosystems.\nBQSTART\nThe historical record shows the commercial exploitation of any species always results in diminished biodiversity.\nBQEND\nThis is probably the crux of one of your arguments, but I think it's a dubious assertion. A well-run management scheme for even a commercially exploited species can definitely maintain biodiversity levels that would otherwise diminish (e.g. fisheries management schemes that stepped in to prevent total collapse).\nSo the effect of bear h