n the next 1500 years, if atmospheric CO2 concentrations did not exceed 240\u00b15\u2009ppmv.\nBut CO2 was already above 240 ppm before the Industrial Revolution.\nThis early higher CO2 concentration may be related to the development of agriculture, which disrupted the carbon cycle.\nClearance of forests for fields meant fewer trees, so less CO2 was removed from the air.\nPlus other agricultural activities, some producing CH4 (eg rice paddies)\nNow with CO2 over 400 ppm, the Earth is heading into conditions not seen for a very long time - way before modern humans were around.\nThose conditions are not conducive to glaciation.\nSo human activity has taken the Earth out of the repeated cycle of glacials and interglacials that has been going on for a couple of million years.\nWhat is likely outcome?\nA paper worth looking at is -\n\"A human-induced hothouse climate?\" -Kidder & Worsley, 2011\nIt's likely a significant number of humans will survive, but conditions will be complex, with many conflicts over resources, and mass migrations from the tropics.", "recommendation_count": "15", "in_reply_to": "116200854", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "116242695", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1527310332000}, "author": "Elizabeth Connor", "author_id": "16853748", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "Thanks for a good news story that also pays due respect to indigenous hunters.", "recommendation_count": "2", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "116241988", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1527303485000}, "author": "R Anon", "author_id": "17206208", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "Hmm hunt humans, so they haven't been hunted by humans for centuries after all, so its not a basis to do so now is it.", "recommendation_count": "0", "in_reply_to": "116229879", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "116241924", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1527302922000}, "author": "R Anon", "author_id": "17206208", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "BQSTART\n