l changes, any more than it is solely responsible for all temperatures changes. As you've pointed out, other factors affect sea levels, including ocean circulation, wind effects, subsidence, ENSO-related water storage, and so on.\nIt stands to reason that in locations where SLR exceeds the global average (hotspots), these other effects are likely to be overwhelming the climate change component.\nBut this in no way decreases the importance of climate change - in fact, it makes things worse, by causing some of the impacts of climate change to manifest earlier than they would have otherwise.\nIt's also worth noting that human activities such as water or hydrocarbon extraction and farming are capable of causing subsidence directly, or magnifying natural subsidence.", "recommendation_count": "3", "in_reply_to": "115404809", "causal_relations": [{"cause": null, "effect": "subsidence"}]}, {"id": "115413046", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1525370649000}, "author": "JonathanHughes", "author_id": "12031469", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "If Mr Rignot is right (probably Dr Rignot!) which is entirely possible then we really are toast!", "recommendation_count": "2", "in_reply_to": "115412429", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "115412994", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1525370564000}, "author": "Thomas1178", "author_id": "17571204", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "Hawaii was \u201cunder\u201d the British flag for a whole 23 years, ending in 1816. The Hawaiians much preferred their own monarchy, which they had throughout the 19th century. I\u2019m not sure history is telling you much\u2026", "recommendation_count": "0", "in_reply_to": "115386696", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "115403474", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1525355067000}, "author": "mikedow", "author_id": "3887757", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "The loss of The Intracoastal Waterway will have a huge impact on marine transportation for the whole East Coa