50517594230784", "recommendation_count": "0", "in_reply_to": "115485848", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "115485848", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1525535814000}, "author": "guest90", "author_id": "17280722", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "There are basically one of two options that will lead to decarbonised shipping. The first is the substitution of Heavy Fuel Oil or Marine Fuel Oil with hydrogen, in increasing percentages, in a a (slightly modified) conventional engine. This has been successfully achieved to 100% hydrogen in a Volvo FH16 Heavy Duty truck by a UK company called ULEMCo, and is efficient. In fact, it easily has the potential (depending on the cost of hydrogen) to be more efficient than diesel. The price per kilometer with electrolysed hydrogen from renewable electricity at about \u20ac40-60/MWh is maybe 50% less than diesel. And this is with a relatively simple modification of the existing engine; they do hydrogen retrofits for all different types of vehicles, and they all run very successfully. Its a fairly new development, because the (potential) price of hydrogen has only recently got down to the \u20ac5-7/kg level recently; and it will improve further. So thats that; this is the way to decarbonise shipping; retrofit existing ship engines and have an electrolyser at the port and some storage and just do it.\nThe other way to decarbonise is to use a fuel cell rather than an IC engine, which is basically 2 times more efficient than an IC engine. So this is will likely be more possible for ships in a decade or so; although it will obviously be the preferred choice eventually as the savings will be very significant.\nThe other issue with using hydrogen in an IC engine as they are starting to do now with trucks is that you can have a part-hydrogen part-existing fuel so you can decarbonise incrementally. \nI think really they all know this but they don't want to tell everyone because of the cost and hassle - its just easier than 