e to restrictions on sail size imposed by the need to pass under harbour bridges. However, JAMDA's figures indicated fuel savings of up to 30% compared to similar conventional vessels.So why didn't they take off? Simple. The oil price dropped, so ship owners could no longer be bothered paying the extra initial cost for more efficient ships. This was despite JAMDA using a sail design which, while not the most efficient out there, met the owner's requirements for a sail system that added less than 10% to the ship's build cost, and did not interfere with loading and unloading. It is good to see that the issue is being revisited, but depressing to think what could have been achieved over the last 30 years if the industry had been less short sighted.", "recommendation_count": "12", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "restrictions on sail size imposed by the need to pass under harbour bridges", "effect": "the larger ships were less efficient"}]}, {"id": "115435757", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1525425886000}, "author": "Celtiberico", "author_id": "3178420", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "Well, most sailboats these days have a petrol-fuelled engine for when there isn't much wind. While this is a sensible precaution, the experience is not exactly enhanced by the noise and fumes, or by the guilt of producing pollution for no good reason. So a battery-powered yacht which could glide silently through the waters would be a distinct improvement.", "recommendation_count": "0", "in_reply_to": "115422603", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "115435740", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1525425868000}, "author": "mabamabam", "author_id": "12512918", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "\"Local production saves a LOT of pollution because these ships are not involved.\"\nThese ships are extremely efficient for the amount they move. Lots of small inefficient factories with less transport is going to use more energy than one highly optimised factory with more