 will be, as addressed in the article, the loss of the effect of saline water freezing onto existing circim-polar sub-zero C sea ice, which by crystallising out some of the water generates a more saline, and thus more dense high-salinity liquid fraction which then sinks down nto the ocean depths and flows slowly back towards the Gulf of Mexico. That returning high-salt, dense and deep current is a driver of the warm surface counter-current we call the Gulf Stream. And if we no longer have a sufficiently cold arctic to drive the fractional crystallisation on which it depends, then the Warm Gulf Stream may die. OK?", "recommendation_count": "6", "in_reply_to": "115715536", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "only global warming has added thermal energy to its environment", "effect": "it melts"}]}, {"id": "115759914", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1526226543000}, "author": "quietreason", "author_id": "14769888", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "A good point. The problem with dykes, sea walls and movable dams such as the UK's Thames barrier is their extreme sensitivity to the combined effects of sea level and wave height.\nWhile sea levels are rising at a seemingly modest 3mm/year that rate of rise is itself accelerating. And all indications are that future events resulting from global warming will induce step change increases in that rate.\nWhen a storm causes a few wave peaks to overtop a barrier, that is rarely a problem as it is only the wave tips, and only a few of them. As the mean sea level rises, and/or the wave heights rise due to increasing storm intensities, the amount and frequency by which those waves overtop those walls also rise, as does the total length of that part of each wave which overtops the wall.\nEach of these factors greatly increases the total influx per unit length of sea wall. Which means that the rate of seawater influx over the wall rises dramatically,out of all proportion to the increase in sea level and/or storm intensity.\nAnd this is why, as you say, our largest cities, and extensive coastal plains (which form much of our habitable and arable lands), are likely to be suddenly and irrecoverably inundated in the uncomfortably near future.", "recommendation_count": "5", "in_reply_to": "115726177", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "a storm", "effect": "a few wave peaks to overtop a barrier"}, {"cause": "increasing storm intensities", "effect": "the wave heights rise"}]}, {"id": "115759272", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1526224838000}, "author": "chrisbrown", "author_id": "3684556", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "Try rereading my remarks instead of just placatively reposting them in your own context. I did not attack anyone: you may have misunderstood my remarks about Scott and Wegener for some reason, and there I was being sarcastic. \nYou are still missing the basic point: the geothermal conditions on Antarctica have not been reported to be different from usual and in any case would not be sufficient to cause the ice loss on Antarctica. The particular subject you mentioned; geothermal effects on glaciers is well known. Why would you want to believe that it was ignored up till now (ie. \"new\"=? I mentioned Iceland and Mt Erebus in case you were unaware of them. They are basic geographical knowledge that are explained in any decent introduction to Geography. Most Atlases have some discussion of them.", "recommendation_count": "3", "in_reply_to": "115743455", "causal_relations": [{"cause": null, "effect": "the ice loss on antarctica"}]}, {"id": "115753184", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1526210772000}, "author": "chrisbrown", "author_id": "3684556", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "Thank you for your perspective from \"down under\". People like me (\"Northerners\") tend to forget Antarctica and its exploration. I can see that this continent and its glaciers are very much a part of your life. I hope a few others stumble upon your comment as it gives a b