ious periods of time in Antarctica and the sub-Antarctic Islands.\nOne a botanist and British citizen was director of the British South Georgia base at the time they captured by the Argentine Navy and held in Buenos Aires. Amid the fervid reports of that war his comment that they were being well treated and fed good Argentine steak was welcome relief. He brought back slides of sled dogs, wonderful scenery and entire plant ecosystems minus vascular plants.\nOne an engineer who overwintered at the Australian base also brought back wonderful slides of dogs, scenery, wildlife and weather. He climbed Mt Erebus and undertook a long motorised overland seismic line journey.\nThe third, 20 years my senior had researched penguins in the early days of the Antarctic Division when Mawson was still alive. Apparently the old blokes party trick at fairly flash gatherings was to talk about and imitate the mating call of the male Leopard Seal to which his wife would answer \"You called dear?\". When under the water, Leopard Seals are truly magnificent animals.", "recommendation_count": "2", "in_reply_to": "115721134", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "115741164", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1526174795000}, "author": "JulesBywaterLees", "author_id": "4738374", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "So what would you ask a glacialogist, or climate scientist working in the cryosphere?\nI suppose I would ask.... can the unexpected happen?the consensus in the IPCC is slowly slowly, just like the end of of the lat glaciation. I not planning for a zombi apocalypse - Im not planning for the 'Day after Tomorrow' but are we all being a little too complacent?", "recommendation_count": "10", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "115740281", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1526171267000}, "author": "glacier", "author_id": "4706143", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "This is a bit unfair. \nRemember that the zero dimensional climate models (which is like all models - just physics) were asked how black-body radiation is affected by having and \"imbrella\". James Hansen did his early years on studying this for other planets at NASA. \nSlowly models became 1 dimensional, and even 2 and 3 dimensional. \nBut at core, they all did a really good job because of how they solve the zero or one-dimensional equations known in the 19th century when it comes to planetary accumulation of heat. \nRemember, as planet, the mean global temperature still is a zero-dimensional problem of that black body. \nThose equations can of course not solve the dynamics of space (and as such - glaciers are space as function of dynamics of incoming and outgoing solar radiation). These original models can not solve the more 3-dimentional equations of why both the ocean and atmosphere move heat from equator to the poles either. \nFact is that models does a fantastic job in solving the energy balance of our planet - because that is a zero order problem. What models do less than fantastic is to simulate the 3 dimensional energy transport as it moves through the 4th dimension of space and interact on the way. \nModellers are tied in by the coastline problem (goggle it) \nIt is a resolution problem. \nThis is important because models are not \"set up\" for something.", "recommendation_count": "8", "in_reply_to": "115729548", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "that is a zero order problem", "effect": "that models does a fantastic job in solving the energy balance of our planet"}, {"cause": "models are not set up for", "effect": "this is important"}]}, {"id": "115729548", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1526155217000}, "author": "Bruce Morgan Williams", "author_id": "11287291", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "The models were never set up to account for all the positive feedbacks that have been discovered over the last decade or two. The probability that they grossly underestimate warming is extremely high.", "recommendation_count": "1", "causal_relations": nu