ny many millions of years,\" he said. \"We think of climate change as occurring 10 years, 100 years, maybe 500 years -- our study has nothing to do with those time scales.\"\nThe NASA study is about the bottom of the ice sheet. Climate change has had an impact on the top of the ice sheet. Warmer ocean waters intruding on the ice shelf causes the ice shelves to break up. When grounded ice sheets exit the land and go into the water that causes sea level rise\n\"This study doesn\u2019t discredit that,\" he says. \"Nothing in our paper has anything to do with climate change.\"\nBQEND\nhttp://www.politifact.com/punditfact/statements/2017/nov/20/americannewscom/no-nasa-antarctica-study-didnt-discredit-climate-c/", "recommendation_count": "5", "in_reply_to": "115628248", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "warmer ocean waters intruding on the ice shelf", "effect": "the ice shelves to break up"}, {"cause": "that", "effect": "sea level rise"}]}, {"id": "115706684", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1526090021000}, "author": "Anthonyhu", "author_id": "17407909", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "BQSTART\nTony could learn something from him, the amount of time AH spends here. Too bad he doesn't seem to be particularly attentive.\nBQEND\nYou do realize the hypocrisy of that statement? Walsunda says: \nBQSTART\nHowever we know there is volcanic activity in Antarctica, because we seen it; and we know there is geothermal flux under the ice in Antarctica because we've measured it from the presence of flowing liquid water.\nBQEND\nThen you make the claim:\nBQSTART\nThe volcanoes on Antarctica must almost all be inactive or they would have been discussed before. The other two next to Mt. Erebus are both dormant, that has been known since James Ross \"discovered them\". We are looking at volcanic activity not erupting volcanoes. Mere seismic activity can have an effect but a minor one on local glaciers.\nBQEND", "recommendation_count": "1", "in_reply_to": "115682477", "causal