rintuitively sea level does not rise uniformly around the world for a number of reasons.\nThere\u2019s the subsidence of land like around river deltas, lift of land from glacial rebound and plate tectonics, ocean currents and winds, and the gravitational fields of the massive ice sheets.\nThe ice sheets have so much mass that they pull the ocean strongly towards them. As they lose mass the ocean relaxes away. So for example the loss of the West Antarctic Ice Sheet would cause 3.3m of GMSLR, but over 4m in the Northern Hemisphere with its more heavily populated coasts.\nParts of the North Atlantic have seen dropping sea levels while parts of the Western Pacific have seen 1.5cm per year over the last decade, roughly five times the global average, which would be problematic for those areas were that rate to continue.", "recommendation_count": "2", "in_reply_to": "115637296", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "the loss of the west antarctic ice sheet", "effect": "3.3 m of gmslr"}]}, {"id": "115653823", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1525963116000}, "author": "chrisbrown", "author_id": "3684556", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "Here is the main statement from the abstract of the link you gave to the Stein et al paper:\"The biomarker proxy records show (i) minimum sea ice extent during the Early Holocene, (ii) a prominent Mid-Holocene short-term high-amplitude variability in sea ice, primary production and Paci\ufb01c-Water in\ufb02ow, and (iii) signi\ufb01cantly increased sea ice extent during the last ca.4.5k cal a BP. This Late Holocene trend in sea ice change in the Chukchi and East Siberian Seas seems to be contemporaneous with similar changes in sea ice extent recorded from other Arctic marginal seas.\"\nSo they are mainly looking at 4.5 thousand years before present. The changes that accompanied the retreat of the last glacial maximum are not in dispute. What the longer term record shows is that we are seeing an unprecedented acceleration in ice loss