l in area compared to the large areas of the coastline where glaciers are in contact with the warming sea.\nAs the NASA site you linked to states \"The stability of an icesheet is closely related to how much water libricates it from below\". Neither of these two links is suggesting that subglacial geothermal melting makes a significant contribution to overall glacial melting, which is why the article above did not mention it in that context. The context of glacial lubrication and destabilization of glaciers grounded below sea level at their downstream end in a warming ocean is a further matter.", "recommendation_count": "6", "in_reply_to": "115628248", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "115667241", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1526012242000}, "author": "DodgyG33za", "author_id": "13029805", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "So we lose New Orleans, Houston and Florida. I am struggling to see the downside :)\nSeriously though, that is what it is going to take before attitudes really change. Human beings are really really bad at taking the long view. Western democracies doubly so.", "recommendation_count": "0", "in_reply_to": "115620748", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "115652911", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1525961252000}, "author": "GuyWarren", "author_id": "13408113", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "Or that the warming is due to a range of factors such as the highest solar activity (not TSI - solar magnetic flux) for 1,000 years, now going into decline, or recovery of global temperatures from an intense cold period when all glaciers were advancing, the first time in the Holocene that had happened.", "recommendation_count": "1", "in_reply_to": "115651526", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "a range of factors such as the highest solar activity for 1,000 years", "effect": "or that the warming is now going into decline"}]}, {"id": "115652763", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1525960943000}, "author": "GuyWarren", "author_id": "13408113",