important issue about feedbacks that occurred as the Antarctica ice sheet melted and discharged fresh cold meltwater into the ocean. \n\"Does this further enhance melting of the ice sheet or does the could fresh water slow it down? It seems that in the Amundsen Sea and Totten glacier region the freshwater discharge forms an insulating cap on the surface ocean because it is less dense,\" Naish said.\n\"This has the affect of reducing deep mixing and allowing warm circumpolar deep water to continue to upwell onto the continental shelf where it comes into contact with the marine margins of the ice sheet enhancing melting.\"\nIn the Ross Sea, however, scientists believed this fresh melt water may end up entrained by the Antarctic slope current, where it was drawn down to greater depths and formed a road block restricting warm ocean currents from reach the ice sheet.\nThis - an example of \"negative\" feedback, as opposed to the \"positive\" feedback highlighted by Silvano - then reduced melting.\n\"It's important to note that this is a high prioirty forefront of research today, and there are still many uncertainties,\" Naish said.\n\"What is clear is that different regions of Antarctica are behaving in different ways, and if we are to understand how fast the ice sheet will melt and contribute to future sea-level rise we need to understand the processes of ocean circulation on the ice sheet margin at the local scale.\"\nBQEND", "recommendation_count": "18", "in_reply_to": "115635163", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "it is less dense", "effect": "that in the amundsen sea and totten glacier region the freshwater discharge forms an insulating cap on the surface ocean"}]}, {"id": "115635511", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1525936965000}, "author": "Walsunda", "author_id": "12483673", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "You say that in Antarctica \"this geothermal heat is a recent discovery previously unknown\"\nAntarctica is the largest glaciovolcanic province in the world. There are many volcanoes and they occur all the way from sub-Antarctic South Sandwich Islands, through the Antarctic Peninsula to Marie Byrd Land, and into East Antarctica, a distance of about 5,000 km. Eruptions coincided with the development of the Antarctic Ice Sheet. The volcanoes are overwhelmingly basaltic and the are few examples of more evolved magmatic compositions. They range from very large stratovolcanoes with elevations up to 4,000 metres and basal diameters of 40 to 60 km, to volcanic fields composed of multiple small centres. The individual volcanoes are often extremely beautiful but the extensive cover of snow and ice and the remote locations can make accessing themquite challenging.\nUnlike lower-latitude volcanoes which are typically obscured extensively vegetation, volcanic outcrops in Antarctica are characteristically very clean and beautifully exposed. In places such as North Victoria Land, cliff sections up to 2 km high extend 10 to 20 km laterally. However, many volcanoes have minimal exposure or have been extensively removed by multiple overriding ice-sheets, particularly in the Antarctic Peninsula. A curiosity of subglacially erupted volcanoes is that, because they are formed of alternating thick sections of lavas and fragmental rocks and are therefore technically stratovolcanoes, the fequent development of lava-fed deltas has resulted in volcano slopes of less than 15 degrees that are normally associated with (lava dominated) shield volcanoes. Both terms have been used to describe Antarctic volcanoes.\nThe above is by Prof John Smellie\nThe West Antarctic Ice sheet has many subglacial lakes beneath it; geothermal heating is thought to contribute to the melting of the base of the West Antarctic Ice Sheet. However, the extent of this, and the rate, is very poorly known and currently not included in glaciological numerical models. Actual volcanoes may, during eruptions, melt quite large portions of the ice sheet around them. In Iceland volcanic eruptions, beneath the ice sheet, regularly cause catastrophic floods, called jokulhlaups. Subglacial volcanoes are therefore contributing at least a little to Antarctic Ice Sheet melt; the extent to which this is happening is probably reasonably stable over longer time scales.\nThe above is by Bethan Davies.\nBoth extracts above are from Antarctic Glaciers.org.\nThe presence of volcanic activity under and breaking through the vast Antarctic Ice Sheet has been known and studied for some time.\nIn 1979 a New Zealand Airlines tourist day trip to Antarctica crashed into Mt Erebus killing all 257 people on board.", "recommendation_count": "16", "in_reply_to": "115631805", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "they are formed of alternating thick sections of lavas and fragmental rocks and are therefore technically stratovolcanoes", "effect": "a curiosity of subglacially erupted volcanoes is that"}, {"cause": "the fequent development of lava fed deltas", "effect": "volcano slopes of less than 15 degrees that are normally associated with"}, {"cause": null, "effect": "catastrophic floods called jokulhlaups"}]}, {"id": "115649453", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1525955812000}, "author": "DavidFTA", "author_id": "4644463", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "BQSTART\nLong-record data shows little sign that circum-Antarctic waters are warming sufficiently to do any melting.\nBQEND\nActually, no, that's not correct: in Konrad et al, Nature Geosciencevolume 11, pages258\u2013262 (2018): \"Net retreat of Antarctic glacier grounding lines\" (https://www.nature.com/articles/s41561-018-0082-z): \nBQSTART\ncombine satellite altimeter observations of ice-elevation change and measurements of ice geometry to track grounding-line movement around the entire continent, tripling the coverage of previous surveys. Between 2010 and 2016, 22%, 3% and 10% of surveyed grounding lines in West Antarctica, East Antarctica and at the Antarctic Peninsula retreated at rates fa