r rib muscles to contract forcing you to exhale. Holding your breath beyond this point requires conscious effort. \nIn an atmosphere beyond 3% you immediately exhale upon inhaling. In other words you involuntarily hyperventilate. Hyperventilation can make you feel sick.\nI retreated from an unexplored cave with an atmosphere near 3%. There were large numbers of loose boulders above a small streamway that was the source of the CO2 and I didn't fancy being pinned under one of those boulders in the streamway below where the CO2 was higher.", "recommendation_count": "3", "in_reply_to": "115623994", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "115632495", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1525926745000}, "author": "Walsunda", "author_id": "12483673", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "At that time there were no humans let alone any human civilisation.", "recommendation_count": "3", "in_reply_to": "115620968", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "115632456", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1525926512000}, "author": "surferdave", "author_id": "3324344", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "Thanks Anthonyhu, and I would just add that the heat flux from volcanism is never static, it changes constantly, sometimes rapidly (see Hawaii right now!) and is generally very poorly understood. Some parts of the continental USA have geothermal heat fluxes of 10's of watts per square metre, the global 'average' is not at all a reliable figure because so much of the crust is deep underwater.", "recommendation_count": "6", "in_reply_to": "115632170", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "so much of the crust is deep underwater", "effect": "some parts of the continental usa have geothermal heat fluxes of 10 's of watts per square metre the global average is not at all a reliable figure"}]}, {"id": "115632170", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1525925137000}, "author": "Anthonyhu", "author_id": "17407909", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "Thanks Eric, not sure what your