s as many acres across the West were burned in the 2010s than in the 1970s. The fire season is 105 days longer than it was in the 1970, and is approaching the point where the notion of a fire season will be made obsolete by the reality of year-round wildfires across the West. The situation in some individual states is more extreme: The average number of large fires burning each year on Forest Service land has increased at least 10-fold in the Northern Rocky Mountain states of Wyoming, Idaho, and Montana. In the Pacific Northwest, there are now five times as many large fires burning in a typical year in Washington as there were in the 1970s; in Oregon there are nearly seven times as many.\nBQEND", "recommendation_count": "16", "in_reply_to": "115803323", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "115826778", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1526371706000}, "author": "GoldenAppleCorps", "author_id": "17327071", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "So weather has nothing to do with climate? That is an interesting position.", "recommendation_count": "17", "in_reply_to": "115803323", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "115805958", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1526312156000}, "author": "Atlant", "author_id": "10100421", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "BQSTART\nAfter all, it's only the eighth largest economy in the world, right?\nBQEND\nFifth largest as of a few days ago!", "recommendation_count": "26", "in_reply_to": "115804594", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "115805000", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1526310853000}, "author": "loco_p_man", "author_id": "13126382", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "You say : \nBQSTART\nIncreased wildfires are a useful myth for the alarmists\nBQEND\nThe report says :\"Since 1950, the area burned by wildfires each year has been increasing, as spring and summer temperatures have warmed and spring snowmelt has occurred earlier. During the recent \u201chotter\u201d drought, unusually warm temperatures