 bit less efficient, since 1% or so efficiency loss is nothing compared to the loss that shading can cause.\nIf you have a really shaded location, different panel voltages, Wp's, orientation, pitch etc etc, then a micro-inverter or SolarEdge solution is needed.", "recommendation_count": "1", "in_reply_to": "116228486", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "shading", "effect": "that"}]}, {"id": "116188696", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1527179913000}, "author": "glennmr", "author_id": "17680035", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "The actual average solar insolation for the UK is about 100 w/m2...even for a place like phoenix Arizona it is only about 250 w/m2. So the entire premise of 1000 W/m2 is sooooooooooooo bogus. Solar is fine...the limit of physics still bats last.\nhttps://eosweb.larc.nasa.gov/sse/", "recommendation_count": "1", "in_reply_to": "116171577", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "116185455", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1527175106000}, "author": "Bernie Thomas", "author_id": "17746707", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "\"This conclusion rests upon a number of shaky assumptions. First, it considers not today\u2019s power grid mix, but rather the US Energy Information Administration (EIA)\u2019s projections out to the year 2050. The EIA is notorious for underestimating the growth of clean energy, and projects that coal will continue to supply 22% of US electricity 32 years hence. To put this in perspective, the share of US electricity supplied by coal fell from 51% in 2008 to 31% in 2016.\"\nSo if 22% is wrong because it's based on shaky assumptions, what is the correct percentage?", "recommendation_count": "1", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "it 's based on shaky assumptions", "effect": "if 22 % is wrong"}]}, {"id": "116139119", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1527083970000}, "author": "onthefence", "author_id": "2490315", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "BQSTART\nDanaNuccitelli - No, California's carbon