ed to include all lifeforms then the rights framework becomes incoherent since the sustainability of life on Earth depends on the life/death cycle. In other words if all lifeforms had rights to existence, regeneration and restoration, then food webs would simply break down.\nA responsibility framework on the other hand does not fall into this same incoherency problem and instead facilitates a community based discussion on the common good.\nPersonally I think it is the community orientation of a responsibility framework rather than the individual orientation of a rights framework that provides the true reason why the upper echelons of Western societies focus on rights. It stops the community from having a legal basis from which to have reasoned and rational discussions and debates which holds the destroyers of Nature to account. In other words, the rights framework protects corporations and governments from The Community whereas a responsibility framework would enable everyone to be held to account whether morally, legally or politically. For me, this is the difference between a version of liberalism that is based on the individual and a version of liberalism that is based on the community.", "recommendation_count": "0", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "116165220", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1527148892000}, "author": "LifeinLIFE", "author_id": "2111826", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "Another flaw of the rights framework is that when rights are expanded to include all lifeforms then the rights framework becomes incoherent since the sustainability of life on Earth depends on the life/death cycle. In other words if all lifeforms had rights to existence, regeneration and restoration, then food webs would simply break down.\nA responsibility framework on the other hand does not fall into this same incoherency problem and instead facilitates a community based discussion on the common good.\nPersonally I think it is the community orientation of a r