 last year. The body is focused on business cooperation.\nBy its own description, the foundation \u201cstarted with a small group of businessmen chatting at the airport while waiting for their flight, wanting to do something to help the Great Barrier Reef\u201d. When asked, the government was not immediately able to say who these businessmen were.\nThe move to direct more than $443 million to this small foundation was so left-field it caught even its beneficiaries off guard. \u201cIt\u2019s like we\u2019ve won lotto,\u201d chief executive Anna Marsden told Fairfax\u2019s Peter Hannam. \u201cWe\u2019re getting calls from a lot of friends.\u201d\nMarsden said the organisation was seeking advice on how to cope with the sudden influx of funds.\nBQEND\nLabor has lodged a freedom of information request. \nOthers have pointed to the foundation\u2019s links to corporate Australia, including fossil fuel behemoths BHP, Shell and Peabody Energy, as well as key banking figures.\n\u201cGod help the Barrier Reef,\u201d was the blunt response of Professor Terry Hughes, the director of the Australian Research Council\u2019s Centre of Excellence for Coral Reef Studies, who has been indefatigable in his scorn for untested scientific solutions such as sun-shields, underwater fans and anything that fails to address the core issues of global warming and immediate decarbonising of the economy.\nSimilarly, acting chief executive of the Climate Council Dr Martin Rice described the focus on water quality and culling starfish as \u201ca golden Band-Aid solution, because it\u2019s not really getting to the root cause of the problem with the bleaching, and that\u2019s climate change.\n\u201cWhen you look at emissions, we\u2019ve had three years of emissions rising in Australia, and any true test of effective climate policy comes down to whether our emissions are going up or down. So there is no credible energy or climate policy in Australia \u2026 [Our] emission reduction targets of 28 per cent are woefully inadequate; they\u2019re not aligned with the science,\u201d he said.\n\u201cIf the world was to go with Australia\u2019s Paris commitments, we would be on target for a 3 to 4 degree [increase in temperature], and that\u2019s devastating. We\u2019re not going to see our iconic Great Barrier Reef survive that. And that\u2019s not just an environmental issue; it\u2019s an economic one.\u201d\nTen days before the government\u2019s announcement, the scale of the threat to the Great Barrier Reef \u2013 and the calamity it has already experienced \u2013 was brutally spelled out in a new paper published by Nature, which The Atlantic described as \u201ca kind of autopsy report for the debacle\u201d.\nTerry Hughes was the lead author of a team of 16 international researchers.\nHughes has stated in preliminary findings that one in every two corals had died. \nUsually, this happens slowly. When subjected to heat stress, coral species expel the algae that both provides them with their colour and with nourishment. If the algae don\u2019t return quickly to recolonise the corals, they starve.\nIn the waters around and north of Port Douglas, previously the most pristine section of the park, the water was so hot that the corals died more or less instantly. \u201cThey cooked,\u201d Hughes said.\n\u201cYou could say it has collapsed. You could say it has degraded. I wouldn\u2019t say that\u2019s wrong,\u201d Hughes told The Atlantic. \u201cA more neutral way of putting it is that it has transformed into a completely new system that looks differently, and behaves differently, and functions differently, than how it was three years ago.\u201d\nSignificant questions remain about the Turnbull government\u2019s motivations and its processes. \nThe funding allocation remains deeply curious.\n Again we see the federal government outsourcing what would normally be the work of a government agency to a private body. \nhttps://www.thesaturdaypaper.com.au/news/environment/2018/05/26/who-the-group-awarded-443m-save-the-reef/15272568006280", "recommendation_count": "4", "in_reply_to": "116346344", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "it \u2019s not really getting to the root cause of the problem with the bleaching and that \u2019s climate change", "effect": "similarly acting chief executive of the climate council dr martin rice described the focus on water quality and culling starfish as \u201c a golden band aid solution"}]}, {"id": "116346406", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1527546933000}, "author": "Notjimdewar", "author_id": "3962644", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "BQSTART\nthe politicians and wealthy so they can spend more time jetting around the world on taxpayer funded junkets\nBQEND\nYou are describing the current mob of deplorables to a T - as well as their current behaviour.", "recommendation_count": "2", "in_reply_to": "116343614", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "116347014", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1527548807000}, "author": "OvlovS60", "author_id": "18394471", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "no, its a pity you didn't but that all conservative politicians didn't conserve their spermatzoa. We'd all be better off.", "recommendation_count": "0", "in_reply_to": "116341097", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "116347002", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1527548786000}, "author": "timthegrate", "author_id": "13012353", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "Land clearing os not just a Qld/NSW issue either.... WA farmers continue to clear massively with their 2ha a year allowance that they have been rorting since its introduction in 2006. It doesnt sound like much but it equates to 200 mature (300+yr old trees) every year for the last 12 years.", "recommendation_count": "3", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "116346394", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1527546892000}, "author": "Leonionis111", "author_id": "13176770", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "On ya Tim, you would be s