 El Nino Southern Oscillation (ENSO) which changes phase around the middle of each calendar year. 2015-16 was an extreme El Nino, 2016-17 was on the borderline between neutral and La Nina while 2017-18 has been a weak La Nina. These ENSO phase changes have caused global yearly temperatures to drop over the last few years. Global climate temperature represents the long term trend which reflects.\nIncreasing levels of CO2 mean more heat is retrained each year but only 6% to 7% of that extra heat goes to warm the atmosphere resulting in the the global climate temperatures we see. During La nina and neutral years heat moves from the atmosphere to the oceans resulting in a cooler gobal temperature compared to a preceding El Nino year. This is what happened from 2015-16 through 2016-17 to 2017-18.\nIs the temperature of the global climate changing? To measure global climate you need to measure successive overlapping 30 year periods of global temperatures. The global climate is getting hotter as the level of atmospheric CO2 increases.", "recommendation_count": "5", "in_reply_to": "116436986", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "these enso phase changes", "effect": "global yearly temperatures to drop over the last few years"}, {"cause": null, "effect": "the the global climate temperatures we see"}, {"cause": null, "effect": "a cooler gobal temperature"}]}, {"id": "116508260", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1527923978000}, "author": "ID2310987", "author_id": "2515806", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "BQSTART\nWhy do you keep skirting around his failed predictions?\nBQEND\nComical given that although you are big on quotes you ignored Svensmark saying warming has stopped and cooling begun nearly ten years ago. Now you've been forced to respond you decide he's right because he maintains that there's been no significant warming. So he's right even when he's wrong. The rest of your post is just an evidence and science free gish gallop.", "recommendation_count": "4",